            "body": "> > As far as I can tell, this added function seems to be working. Am I missing some remaining issues before it will be approved?\r\n> \r\n> Yes it works. But I have a nagging feeling that there might be some edge cases that I haven't handled. Actually, this one \ud83d\udc47\ud83c\udffb still needs a unit test\r\n> \r\n>     * [ ]  Ensure that PROJ4 projections with spaces (e.g. projection=\"+proj4=+longlat +ellipsoid=someplanet\") work, xref -JEPSG:4326 not writing CRS to netcdf in surface [-JEPSG:4326 not writing CRS to netcdf in surface #655](https://github.com/GenericMappingTools/pygmt/issues/655) (comment)\r\n\r\nOk, PROJ4 strings with spaces now work as of 3ec772740823a12f906210edeed5284aa101ff12 :tada: I just deleted the spaces for arguments in -J (projection) and it works, since GMT allows it (xref https://github.com/GenericMappingTools/gmt/blob/c697c355f39619911ffca266788e818c6ffce73e/doc/rst/source/explain_-Jproj_full.rst_#L9-L11)\r\n\r\nEdit: There's one test failure on Windows at https://github.com/GenericMappingTools/pygmt/runs/5440961826?check_suite_focus=true#step:11:669 `NotADirectoryError: [WinError 267] The directory name is invalid: 'D:\\\\a\\\\pygmt\\\\pygmt\\\\tmp-test-dir-with-unique-name\\\\results\\\\pygmt.tests.test_basemap.test_basemap_utm_projection_EPSG:32723 +width=5'` to do with saving filenames with a colon `:` (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10386344/how-to-get-a-file-in-windows-with-a-colon-in-the-filename). I'll see if I can fix it... \r\n\r\nEdit2: Ok, Windows failures have been resolved. All checks passing at 36fdec540df8b1cb6c925f7f916752944a6374f1.",
